text.tspan: Clients (Web browser and native mobiles) connect to Tavendo WebMQ via WebSocket - a new IETF
specified open protocol already built into modern browsers.
WebSocket is the new standard for real-time messaging on the Web and allows for bi-directional, low-latency
communication over persistent and efficient connections.
While WebSocket provides a solid low-level communication foundation, Tavendo WebMQ provides
two powerful higher-level messaging patterns to applications via WAMP:
At it's core, Tavendo WebMQ then dispatches PubSub messages from both clients and Oracle, and
forwards client RPCs to Oracle stored procedures.
Events can also be published to a REST API, and client RPCs can be remoted to REST API calls.
This allows quick and easy extension of existing Web applications, as well as the parallel integration
of Web application servers and Oracle databases into your projects.
WebMQ is principally deliverd as an industry-standard virtual appliance image, ready to run on
the virtualization solution of your choice.
Administration is via a graphical UI that runs in the browser.
Tavendo WebMQ enables the creation of Web and mobile applications powered directly from your database
without an application server and without any coding on the middletier.
Tavendo WebMQ realizes this architecture by acting as a bidirectional real-time message bus between
browser and mobile app instances and the database:
In this architecture, user interface logic is implemented completely in browser or mobile app frontends
using JavaScript, HTML5 and CSS standards or native mobile languages, and business logic is
implemented within the database, nearby your data in database procedural SQL dialects.
Please note that no application code is run on Tavendo WebMQ. All application specific code is either
run in the frontends or the database. Hence, the architecture is logically 2-layer, which greatly simplifies

flowRoot.flowPara: The PubSub pattern allows for asynchronous, decoupled communication between clients.
Clients publish events to topics. Tavendo WebMQ then dispatches events to all client currently subscribed on that topic.
Tavendo WebMQ allows to publish events to topics directly from within database stored procedures or triggers.
You can publish structured payload (JSON objects) from PL/SQL using the JSON utility packages included with Tavendo WebMQ.
Tavendo WebMQ allows you to call database stored procedures from JavaScript running in Web browsers or native mobile clients.
